Example \(\PageIndex{4}\) Compute the average rate of change of \(f(x)=x^{2} -\dfrac{1}{x}\) on the interval [2, 4]. Solution We can start by computing the function values at each endpoint of the interval \[f(2)=2^{2} -\dfrac{1}{2} =4-\dfrac{1}{2} =\dfrac{7}{2} 
onumber\] \[f(4)=4^{2} -\dfrac{1}{4} =16-\dfrac{1}{4} =\dfrac{63}{4} 
onumber\] Now computing the average rate of change \[	ext{Average rate of change} = \dfrac{f(4) - f(2)}{4 - 2} =\dfrac{\dfrac{63}{4} -\dfrac{7}{2} }{4-2} =\dfrac{\dfrac{49}{4} }{2} = \dfrac{49}{8} 
onumber\]

Example \(\PageIndex{5}\) The magnetic force \(F\), measured in Newtons, between two magnets is related to the distance between the magnets \(d\), in centimeters, by the formula \(F(d)=\dfrac{2}{d^{2} }\). Find the average rate of change of force if the distance between the magnets is increased from 2 cm to 6 cm. Solution We are computing the average rate of change of \(F(d)=\dfrac{2}{d^{2} }\) on the interval [2, 6]. Average rate of change = \(\dfrac{F(6) - F(2)}{6 - 2}\) Evaluating the function \[\dfrac{F(6)-F(2)}{6-2} =
onumber \] \[= \dfrac{\dfrac{2}{6^{2} } -\dfrac{2}{2^{2} } }{6-2}
onumber \] Simplifying \[= \dfrac{\dfrac{2}{36} -\dfrac{2}{4} }{4}
onumber \] Combining the numerator terms \[= \dfrac{\dfrac{-16}{36} }{4}
onumber \] Simplifying further \[= \dfrac{-1}{9}
onumber \] Newtons per centimeter This tells us the magnetic force decreases, on average, by 1/9 Newtons per centimeter over this interval.

Example \(\PageIndex{6}\) Find the average rate of change of \(g(t)=t^{2} +3t+1\)on the interval \([0, a]\). Your answer will be an expression involving a . Solution Using the average rate of change formula \[\dfrac{g(a)-g(0)}{a-0}
onumber\] Evaluating the function \[\dfrac{(a^{2} +3a+1)-(0^{2} +3(0)+1)}{a-0}
onumber\] Simplifying \[\dfrac{a^{2} +3a+1-1}{a}
onumber\] Simplifying further, and factoring \[\dfrac{a(a+3)}{a}
onumber\] Cancelling the common factor \(a\) \[a+3
onumber\] This result tells us the average rate of change between t = 0 and any other point t = a . For example, on the interval [0, 5], the average rate of change would be 5+3 = 8.
